  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "IntroductionThe exponential growth of terminals in fifth generation (5G) mobile networks has led to an increasingly congested spectrum resource, requiring viable techniques to deal with it [1].",
    "Apart from novel multiple access techniques [2][3][4], opening the radar-assigned spectrum to wireless communication is another promising solution, i.e., radar and communication coexistence [5,6].",
    "Specifically, radar and communication systems are two separate identities with overlapped frequency bands, requiring a cooperative effort to mitigate mutual interference.",
    "This can be facilitated by various interference cancellation techniques such as opportunistic spectrum access [7], precoding [8], and waveform design [9].",
    "However, all these techniques require frequent information exchange between the two systems, resulting in a limited spectral efficiency improvement in practice [10].By exploiting the hardware architecture and signal processing similarities between radar and communication systems, communication and sensing functionalities can be further integrated into a unified platform, sharing the same hardware and spectrum resource to significantly reduce cost, hardware size, and power consumption [11]."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
